			<div class="col rounded">

				<ul class="p-3">
					<li>Both sides wear deep green but Cordelia's dresses are much more elaborate than Theodore's work clothes</li>
					<li>Any jewellery she wears is gold, including a plain wedding band (How to make people think you're married 101)</li>
					<li>As Theodore, he simply ties his hair and/or tucks it in his hat</li>
					<li>His scars (<i class="far fa-arrow-left"></i>) don't have to be followed particularly closely, they don't have any important placements or significance other than I Like Drawing Them TM</li>
					<li>Has a lot of options for clothes! See image 4 for inspo -- if you'd like to find smth else, I tend to stick to 1850-1910 ish. The main dress I draw her in is based on <a href="https://www.osfcostumerentals.org/ItemDetail/09005680/women-s-bodices-1890-b34-black-silk-beaded-sleeveless-boddice-with-gold-beaded-shoulder-zippered-underflap-floral-sidewaist-good-condition">this real one</a>, though I usually omit the embroidery bcus it's hard to draw lol</li>
					    <ul>
					        <li>Cordelia wears elaborate dresses with slim silhouettes (minimal/no petticoats), long sleeves, high collars, wide brim hats</li>
					        <li>Theodore wears nice waistcoats but is otherwise fairly plain, more focus on practicality and movement, often rolls up shirt sleeves, bowler hats</li>
					    </ul>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
		<div class="col-md-6 col-lg-4 pr-0">
			<div class="col p-2 rounded text-center" style="background-color:rgba(38, 102, 39,0.5);">
				okay but what does that that mean
			</div>
			<div class="col rounded">

				<ul class="p-3">
					<li>In modern terms, Pembroke is one person who is genderfluid with a very situational view on gender and uses she/he but not they</li>
					<li>When talking about her as an individual, I tend to just pick/alternate between her pronouns, usually defaulting to she as I have another oc in her circle that uses he</li>
					<li>Acceptable names and nicknames include: Cordelia (Delia, Delilah), Theodore (Theo), Pembroke (Pem, Broke/Brooke)</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			
